As a professional social science researcher I would not have approved this research design. It is a thinly-veiled piece of research that will more than likely yield results that can be used against the current U. S. President. As an example of a major design issue, those who designed this instrument ought to define terms that are in common parlance but inaccurate. I give two examples: (1) The U. S. has a republican form of government. Several questions that ask about the degree to which actions or policies are or are not democratic are essentially irrelevant to the form of government. (2) The U. S. Constitution centers on the rights and responsibilities of "the several states" as agents of the people. It is representation of the states, whether populous or not, that is important. This FACT seems to be missing from modern education. As a result, current attacks on the "undemocratic" electoral college are enthusiastically welcomed in some circled. Even those who defend the electoral college are often on shaky argumentative grounds because they do not understand completely why the college was created.
